revision.text:
{{Year box}} '''1779 in sports''' describes the year's events in world sport.
==[[Boxing]]== '''Events''' * 25 September — Duggan Fearns defeated Harry Sellers at [[Slough]] by a first-round knockout after 1 minute and 30 seconds to claim the Championship of England title. This is the only fight in which Fearns is known to have been involved and little is known of him except that he was born c.1754 in Ireland. He never defended his title which was eventually reclaimed by Sellers. The next known title fight was not until 1785 when Sellers met William Harvey.<ref>[http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/fearns-duggan.htm Cyber Boxing Zone – Duggan Fearns]. Retrieved on 7 November 2009.</ref>
==[[Cricket]]== '''Events''' * [[Hampshire county cricket teams|Hampshire]] defeated the [[Non-international England cricket teams|England XI]] four times. '''England''' * Most runs<ref name="cards">Note that scorecards created in the 18th century are not necessarily accurate or complete; therefore any summary of runs, wickets or catches can only represent the '''known''' totals and the missing data prevents effective computation of averages</ref> – [[Richard Aubrey Veck]] 280 * Most wickets<ref name="cards"/> – [[Lamborn (Hambledon cricketer)|Lamborn]] 18
==[[Horse racing]]== '''Events''' * Inaugural running of [[Epsom Oaks|The Oaks]], sometimes called the Epsom Oaks for differentiation purposes, on [[Epsom Downs Racecourse|Epsom Downs]]. The second-oldest of the five [[British Classic Races]], the race is named after [[Oaks Park (London)|Oaks Park]], an estate located to the east of [[Epsom]] which was leased to the [[Edward Smith-Stanley, 12th Earl of Derby|12th Earl of Derby]] in the 18th century.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Punter's Friend |last1=Waterman |first1=Jack |year= 1999 |publisher=Queen Anne Press |location=Harpenden, Herts, UK |isbn=1852916001 }}</ref> '''England''' * [[Epsom Oaks|The Oaks]] – Bridget * [[St Leger Stakes]] – Tommy
