[[File:Ronnie O'Sullivan's first maximum break.gif|thumb|upright=1.35|[[Ronnie O'Sullivan]]'s maximum at the 1997 World Championship. This holds the [[#Chronometrical|record for the fastest 147]].]] 

In [[snooker]], under normal circumstances, the '''maximum [[Break (snooker)|break]]''' is 147,<ref name="British Phrasebook">{{cite book|first1=Elizabeth|last1=Bartsch-Parker|first2=Roibeard|last2=O'Maolalaigh|first3=Stephen|last3=Burger|title=British Phrasebook|year=1999|publisher=Lonely Planet|location=Hawthorn, Vic.|isbn=0-86442-484-1|page=146|url=https://books.google.hu/books?id=qcR7uwgf5BEC&pg=PA146&dq=%22maximum+break%22+snooker&hl=hu&sa=X&ei=OUe1T-XqEsPStAaq9JnDDA&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22maximum%20break%22%20snooker&f=false|edition=1st|accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref> also known as a '''maximum''', a '''147''', or orally, a '''one-four-seven'''. This score is attained by potting all 15 {{Cuegloss|Red ball|reds}} with 15 {{Cuegloss|Black ball|blacks}} for 120 points, followed by all six {{Cuegloss|Colour ball|colours}} for a further 27 points, all in a single {{Cuegloss|break}} i.e. without any misses.<ref name="British Phrasebook"/>

[[Joe Davis]] made the first officially recognised maximum break in a 1955 exhibition match in London. In 1982, [[Steve Davis]] achieved the first recognised maximum in professional competition, which was also the first maximum to occur during a [[Broadcasting of sports events|televised match]]. The following year, [[Cliff Thorburn]] became the first player to make a maximum in [[1983 World Snooker Championship|a World Championship]].

Maximum breaks have always been rare in snooker. It took until 2013 for 100 maximums to be scored in professional competition.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/25284182|title=UK Snooker Championship 2013: Selby makes 100th 147 break|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=7 December 2013|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> However they have gradually become more frequent in the game. Only eight maximums were achieved in the 1980s, but 26 were attained in the 1990s and 35 in the 2000s. So far in the 2010s, over 70 maximums have been achieved.

The record for the [[#Total maximum breaks|most maximum breaks in professional competition]] is held by [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] with 15. He also holds the [[#Chronometrical|record for the fastest competitive maximum break]], at just over five minutes, which he achieved at the [[1997 World Snooker Championship|1997 World Championship]]. 

Breaks greater than 147 are possible if there is a {{Cuegloss|free ball}} before any of the reds have been potted, though this situation is itself extremely unusual. Only one break of over 147 has occurred in professional competition, when [[Jamie Burnett]] made a break of 148 in the qualifying stages of the [[2004 UK Championship (snooker)|2004 UK Championship]].

{{TOC limit|2}}

==History==
[[Joe Davis]] compiled the first officially recognised maximum break on 22 January 1955, in a match against [[Willie Smith (billiards player)|Willie Smith]] at [[Leicester Square Hall]], London.<ref name="times24jan1955">{{cite news |newspaper=The Times |date=24 January 1955 |page=12 |title=Maximum Snooker Record}}</ref> The [[Billiards Association and Control Council]] initially refused to accept the break since the match was not played under their rules. At the time the professionals played using a rule (now standard) whereby after a foul a player could compel the offender to play the next stroke. It was only at a meeting on 20 March 1957 that they recognised the break. Davis was presented with a certificate to commemorate his achievement.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The Times |date=21 March 1957 |page=4 |title=J Davis's Record Recognized}}</ref> The match between Davis and Smith was played as part of a series of events marking the closure of Leicester Square Hall. The hall, known as Thurston's Hall until 1947,<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The Times |date=18 September 1947 |page=6 |title=Billiards and Snooker}}</ref> had hosted many important billiards and snooker matches since its opening in 1901, including 12 [[World Snooker Championship]] finals.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The Times |date=17 January 1955 |page=3 |title=Farewell Leicester Square - Hall of Memories lost to Billiards}}</ref> 

[[John Spencer (snooker player)|John Spencer]] made the first tournament maximum break in the 1979 Holsten Lager International, but this did not count as an official maximum as the break was made on a non-templated table used during the event.<ref name="Snooker.org"/> The first official maximum break in professional competition was by [[Steve Davis]] in the [[1982 Classic (snooker)|1982 Classic]] at the Queen Elizabeth Hall in [[Oldham]], against [[John Spencer (snooker player)|John Spencer]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson |first=Jeremy |title=Stephen Hendry progress in balance despite 147 maximum break |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/snooker/5238033/Stephen-Hendry-progress-in-balance-despite-147-maximum-break.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK |accessdate=14 May 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z8pYGGGV?url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/snooker/5238033/Stephen-Hendry-progress-in-balance-despite-147-maximum-break.html |archivedate= 2 June 2011 |date=28 April 2009 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> winning a car for the achievement.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/article/663/9062843/snookers-historic-maximum-breaks| title = Snooker's historic maximum breaks | accessdate = 14 February 2014| date = 7 December 2013| publisher=SportingLife}}</ref> This was also the first televised maximum.<ref name="Guinness-Davis"/> The following year, [[Cliff Thorburn]] became the first player to make a maximum at the [[1983 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], in the fourth frame of his second round match against [[Terry Griffiths]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/article/663/9062843/snookers-historic-maximum-breaks|title=Snooker's historic maximum breaks|accessdate=14 February 2014|date=7 December 2013|publisher=[[Sporting Life (British newspaper)|Sporting Life]]}}</ref>

Before the 1994–95 season, the maximum break remained a rare feat, with only 15 compiled official maximums. But starting with 1994–95, a maximum break has been achieved every season thereafter;  the 13 maximums scored in the 2016–17 season is the highest number to date. The one-hundreth officially recognised maximum break in professional competition was made on 7 December 2013 by [[Mark Selby]] in the 7th frame of his semi-final match at the [[2013 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]] against [[Ricky Walden]].<ref name="2013 Selby 147"/> Since then, another 39 maximum breaks have been officially recorded in professional competition.<ref name="Official 147s" /> Englishman [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] has compiled fifteen ratified competitive maximum breaks, the most by any professional player.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rocket Flies To Magical Maximum |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~4346839,00.html |work=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |date=4 December 2014 |accessdate=5 December 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208111600/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~4346839%2C00.html |archivedate=8 December 2014 |df= }}</ref> Following him are [[Stephen Hendry]] with eleven, [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] with eight, and [[Ding Junhui]] with six. O'Sullivan also holds the record for the fastest competitive maximum break at just over 5 minutes, which he set at the [[1997 World Snooker Championship|1997 World Championship]].<ref name=Deadspin />

At least seven players have missed the final black on 140: [[Robin Hull]], [[Ken Doherty]], [[Barry Pinches]], [[Mark Selby]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/more-sports/snooker/news/12243/8601712/near-miss-for-mark-selby-in-easy-win-over-mark-king-in-china|title=Near-miss for Mark Selby in easy win over Mark King in China|publisher=}}</ref> [[Michael White (snooker player)|Michael White]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.love-snooker.com/2253-doherty-secures-austalian-open-place.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-12-02 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208114047/http://www.love-snooker.com/2253-doherty-secures-austalian-open-place.html |archivedate=8 December 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Thepchaiya Un-Nooh]] (twice in the [[Snooker season 2015/2016|2015–16 season]]),<ref>{{cite web|title=Un-Nooh misses black for 147 |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/un-nooh-misses-black-for-147 |work=worldsnooker.com|publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]]|date=1 December 2015 |accessdate=2 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/36028297|title=Thepchaiya Un-Nooh misses final-black maximum again|date=12 April 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> and [[Liang Wenbo]] (in [[2018 World Snooker Championship|2018]]).<ref>http://www.worldsnooker.com/liang-makes-147-misses-black-140/</ref>

[[#Breaks exceeding 147|Breaks above 147]] are possible when an opponent fouls and leaves a {{Cuegloss|free ball}} with all fifteen reds still remaining on the table. A break greater than 147 has happened only once in professional competition, when [[Jamie Burnett]] made a 148-point break at the qualifying stage of the [[2004 UK Championship (snooker)|2004 UK Championship]].<ref name="burnettguardian"/> [[Jamie Cope]] compiled a break of 155 points, the highest possible free-ball break, during practice in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sport.guardian.co.uk/snooker/story/0,10158,1590060,00.html|title=Murphy shows the form and confidence of a champion|date=12 October 2005|first=Clive|last=Everton|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/3750162.stm|title=Scot Burnett compiles 148 break| publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> [[Alex Higgins]] was said to have attained the same feat.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/alex-higgins/alex-higgins-a-155-break-impossible-not-for-higgy-28548775.html|title=Alex Higgins: A 155 break impossible? Not for Higgy|date=26 July 2010|accessdate=3 December 2015|publisher=[[Belfast Telegraph]]}}</ref>

